    "content": "UNESCO and the Federal Government of Somalia have finally moved the needle on digital learning in the war-torn nation, unveiling a bold new ICT in Education Policy and Masterplan that promises to revolutionize how Somali children learn. The move comes after years of civil war, political instability, and the COVID-19 pandemic that left the country's education system in shambles.\n\nOn 25 November 2023, the Ministry of Education, Culture and Higher Education (MoECHE) teamed up with UNESCO to host a crucial hybrid workshop in Mogadishu. The goal? To craft Somalia's first-ever national policy for integrating technology into classrooms. Key players like Director General Mr Mohamed Abbi Hassan and UNESCO expert Dr Shafika Isaacs were on deck to tackle issues like poor internet access, lack of digital literacy, and untrained teachers.\n\nSomalia has been plagued by educational crises since the 1990s, with civil war causing mass displacement and school destruction. But the pandemic acted as a twisted blessing, forcing the Ministry to experiment with distance learning programs. Now, with UNESCO's support, they're taking it to the next level. The workshop also saw participation from Federal Member States' education ministries and online attendees, all aiming to create a cohesive plan for a digital future.\n\nToshiyuki Matsumoto, Education Programme Specialist at UNESCO Nairobi, emphasized that this is just the beginning. 'We are committed to supporting Somalia in building a resilient education system,' he said. With this new policy, Somalia hopes to leapfrog decades of setbacks and give its youth a fighting chance in the digital age.",
