    "content": "Mogadishu, Somalia — In a country where over 3 million children are out of school due to conflict, poverty, and displacement, a new tech-driven initiative is offering a lifeline to visually impaired students. At a school for the blind in Mogadishu, students are among the first to receive Braille-compatible tablets, tools that are common elsewhere but have been virtually unavailable in Somalia.\n\nFor years, Somalia has struggled to provide a unified national curriculum for special needs students. The principal of the school, who oversees dozens of visually impaired children, hopes the program will help establish a standard framework. According to UN data, only four schools in the entire country teach Braille, despite an estimated 360,000 visually impaired Somalis. Students like Aisha, who completed primary school but lacks essential tools, see these tablets as a gateway to continuing their education.\n\nThe initiative is a partnership between Save the Children, the Somali government, and Hormud, a leading telecom firm. It aims to use mobile technology to improve access to education and bring digital literacy closer to vulnerable children. The agreement also includes real-time information sharing during crises such as floods and droughts, a critical need in a country prone to natural disasters.\n\nGovernment officials have welcomed the move, particularly the provision of internet access to public schools to support e-learning. However, they also caution about potential risks. \"This initiative has both positive and negative sides. While smart tablets improve learning, they also risk exposing children to harmful online content like internet games,\" one official said. The program is expected to help improve enrollment rates, but challenges remain in ensuring safe and effective use of technology.",
