    "summary": "Somalia's education system is in shambles as conflict, climate shocks, and poverty leave millions of children without schooling, with attacks on schools disrupting learning for over 150,000 kids in just six months.",
    "content": "The education crisis in Somalia has reached catastrophic levels, with a staggering 3.4 million children—58% of all school-aged children—completely out of school in 2025, according to the latest Education in Emergencies Hub country brief. This dire situation places Somalia among the top ten countries globally with the highest number of crisis-affected children missing out on learning. The average Somali child is projected to receive a mere 1.7 years of schooling in their lifetime, a fraction of the African average of 7.7 years, highlighting the devastating long-term impact on the nation's development.\n\nConflict remains a primary driver of this crisis, with persistent attacks on students, teachers, and school infrastructure. In the first six months of 2025 alone, attacks and military use of schools disrupted education for over 150,000 children. Grave violations against children are alarmingly high, including abductions and forced recruitment that disproportionately affect boys, while sexual violence continues to target girls. These threats force families to keep children at home or flee, further eroding access to education.\n\nClimate shocks compound the problem, with recurrent droughts and floods upending lives. The 2023 El Niño floods displaced an estimated 400,000 children and disrupted learning for nearly 900,000 as schools were damaged or repurposed as shelters. Drought and famine-like conditions repeatedly force school closures as families migrate for survival, causing attendance rates to plummet among newly displaced populations. The cycle of displacement and poverty keeps children out of classrooms, perpetuating a crisis that demands urgent international attention.",
