    "content": "A groundbreaking study published in the Horn Africa Journal of Social Sciences has dropped a bombshell: artificial intelligence is quietly revolutionizing high school education in Banadir, Somalia. The research, led by Abdirahman Osman Ali and Prof Dr Abdullahi Sharif of the Baacil Institute for Research and Development, surveyed 315 students from public and private schools and found that nearly two-thirds are already using AI tools – with ChatGPT being the undisputed king.\n\nThe findings are jaw-dropping: a whopping 84.4% of students say AI has boosted their understanding of subjects, and 79.1% claim it helps them grasp lessons better. Problem-solving skills are the most improved area, reported by nearly half of the users. But it's not all rosy – 44.4% of students face limited internet and device access, 26.3% have encountered inaccurate AI-generated information, and 23.8% find the tools difficult to understand.\n\nDespite these hurdles, an overwhelming 70.5% of students want to continue using AI in their studies and support greater integration in schools. The study also found no significant differences in AI use based on gender, grade level, or school type, suggesting the benefits cut across all demographics. The authors warn, however, that equitable access, teacher training, digital literacy, and clear institutional policies are essential to harness this potential responsibly.",
